<p>If the encoder you are using is the Spark one, I believe this could work</p>
<p>In this case, instead of using the AbsoluteEncoder interface, I access the encoder directly through the controller</p>
<pre><code class="lang-auto">package frc.robot;

import edu.wpi.first.wpilibj.TimedRobot;

import com.revrobotics.spark.SparkAbsoluteEncoder;
//import edu.wpi.first.wpilibj.DigitalInput;
import com.revrobotics.spark.SparkMax;

public class Robot extends TimedRobot {
  SparkMax motorCAN = new SparkMax(2, SparkMax.MotorType.kBrushless);
  SparkAbsoluteEncoder encoder2 = motorCAN.getAbsoluteEncoder();

  double angulo;
  double speed;

  @Override
  public void teleopPeriodic() {
    motorCAN.set(0.1);
    angulo = encoder2.getPosition();

    System.out.println("\n");
    System.out.printf("angulo: %2f", angulo);
  }
}
</code></pre>
<p>or, instead of using SparkAbsoluteEncoder, you can just use AbsoluteEncoder even though it looks like this</p>
<pre><code class="lang-auto">AbsoluteEncoder encoder2 = motorCAN.getAbsoluteEncoder();
